<dl id="n54129q"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54129q">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54129q"> 129(q)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> prakrit, sanscrit,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">5. <i>samskrta</i> (<i>m</i>)&mdash;dont la vieille transcription &laquo;sanscroutan&raquo; rendait mieux en fran&ccedil;ais la prononciation r&eacute;elle&mdash;signifierait bien &laquo;artificiel&raquo; sans la valeur p&eacute;jorative qui s&apos;attache &agrave; ce mot. Comme adjectif, appliqu&eacute; &agrave; un homme, il peut vouloir dire &laquo;parachev&eacute;&raquo; par les sacrements (samsk&acirc;ra) de la seconde naissance, et d&eacute;signer le &laquo;deux-fois-n&eacute;&raquo; (dvija). Le mot <i>pr&acirc;krta</i> signifie &laquo;produit par <mark><i>prakrti</i></mark>&raquo; (la Nature, au sens le plus large). Le <mark><i>sanskrit</i></mark> trouve sa codification d&eacute;finitive dans l&apos;&oelig;uvre de P&Acirc;NINI (VIe ou Ve s. av. J-C.), &agrave; qui la linguistique moderne doit une bonne part de ses progr&egrave;s. <br><font color="green">[5. samskrta&nbsp;(m)&mdash;whose old transcription "sanscroutan" made the real pronunciation better in French&mdash;would mean "artificial" without the pejorative value attached to this word. As an adjective, applied to a man, it can mean "completed" by the sacraments (samsk&acirc;ra) of the second birth, and designate the "twice-born" (dvija). The word pr&acirc;krta means "produced by prakrti" (Nature, in the broadest sense). Sanskrit finds its definitive codification in the work of P&Acirc;NINI (6th or 5th century BC), to whom modern linguistics owes a good part of its progress.]</font> <small> Ren&eacute; Daumal, <a name="RDLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RDLP"><cite title="source">Les pouvoirs de la parole</cite></a> (1938) [82-3]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
